The key insight is that we need to carefully track the relationship in each case. For the `cons` case, when we add a new vertex, we also add a new edge. For the `loop` case, the vertex is already in support.

```lean
lemma vertex_edge_inequality {u v : V} (p : G.LoopWalk u v) :
  (supportSet p).card ≤ (edgeSet p).card +1 := by
  induction p with
  | nil => 
    simp only [supportSet, support, edgeSet, edges, darts, List.map_nil, List.toFinset_nil,
               Finset.card_empty, zero_add, List.toFinset_singleton, Finset.card_singleton]
  | cons h q ih =>
    simp only [supportSet, support, edgeSet, edges, darts, dartEdge, List.map_cons,
               List.toFinset_cons] at *
    have h1 : (Finset.insert u q.support.toFinset).card ≤ q.support.toFinset.card + 1 := 
      Finset.card_insert_le _ _
    have h2 : q.edges.toFinset.card ≤ (Finset.insert (Sym2.mk (u, _)) q.edges.toFinset).card := 
      Finset.card_le_card (Finset.subset_insert _ _)
    have h3 : q.edges.toFinset.card + 1 ≤ (Finset.insert (Sym2.mk (u, _)) q.edges.toFinset).card + 1 := 
      Nat.add_le_add_right h2 1
    exact Nat.le_trans h1 (Nat.le_trans (Nat.add_le_add_right ih 1) 
      (Nat.succ_le_succ h3))
  | loop q ih =>
    simp only [supportSet, support, edgeSet, edges, darts, dartEdge, List.map_cons,
               List.toFinset_cons] at *
    have h1 : (Finset.insert u q.support.toFinset).card ≤ q.support.toFinset.card + 1 := 
      Finset.card_insert_le _ _
    have h2 : q.edges.toFinset.card ≤ (Finset.insert (Sym2.mk (u, u)) q.edges.toFinset).card := 
      Finset.card_le_card (Finset.subset_insert _ _)
    have h3 : q.edges.toFinset.card + 1 ≤ (Finset.insert (Sym2.mk (u, u)) q.edges.toFinset).card + 1 := 
      Nat.add_le_add_right h2 1
    exact Nat.le_trans h1 (Nat.le_trans (Nat.add_le_add_right ih 1) 
      (Nat.succ_le_succ h3))
```
